A total of 261 (21.3%) of the 1224 ILI specimens showed positive results in the Flu Dot-ELISA (Table 1
), and 170 were further confirmed to be influenza through virus culturing, the current reference standard, with a sensitivity of approximately 95% (Table 2
). The other 91 Flu Dot-ELISA–positive samples were negative in virus culture, and six of the 963 Flu Dot-ELISA–negative specimens were later shown to be positive in virus culture. Thus, compared to virus culture, the sensitivity and specificity of the Flu Dot-ELISA for nasopharyngeal swab specimens were 96.6% (170/176, 95% CI 92.7–98.7%) and 91.3% (957/1048, 95% CI 89.4–93.0%), respectively, and the positive predictive and negative predictive values for the border screening were 65.1% (170/261, 95% CI 59.0–70.9) and 99.4% (957/963, 95% CI 98.7–99.8%), respectively.
